Update – Kernel / Veritas Patch Duration
The kernel upgrade took longer than expected because the server is part of a Veritas InfoScale / VCS cluster environment and hosts a larger number of cluster resources compared to the other nodes.
During the patching process, several additional operations are required:
Veritas kernel modules (vxio, vxdmp, vxfen, etc.) must be rebuilt and relinked to match the new kernel version.
The system rebuilds the initramfs, including storage, multipath, and Veritas drivers.
During the reboot phase, the server performs a full SAN device scan and multipath initialization.
The node also contains a higher number of VCS service groups, disk groups, and mounted filesystems, which increases the time required for storage discovery and cluster validation.
Because this node manages more cluster resources than the other servers, the startup validation and storage initialization phases require additional time before the node can fully rejoin the cluster.
This behavior is expected in large clustered environments and does not indicate an issue with the patching process.
